The impact of errors in 2D (and even all-to-all) architectures is much higher than in 1D architectures due to a more rapid propagation of errors. However, this does not necessarily imply that 1D circuits are better for near-term quantum computation since our analysis thus far does not account for the increased connectivity of the quantum circuit. In order to take that into account, in the next subsection we consider a specific case, QAOA for solving a nonlocal problem, i.e., a graph with long-range vertices (a nonplanar graph). This necessarily places us in the deep circuit regime (as defined in Table

 I

) in all cases.
